For my first visit to San Fran, we went to what the web considered the best food here. They were right -- we got the BFC with Mac&cheese, and it was delectable. The jam is impeccable -- we asked for extra. Great service, delicious food!

After having Brenda's bookmarked for FOREVER!!! I finally made my way over to check it out. Honestly, I don't know what took me so long to finally go but I am so glad I did! We went on a Friday around 6:00 pm and shockingly we were seated immediately, I would have thought we had to wait which I would not have mind. Now, onto the important part the FOOD!! We ordered the crawfish, maple bacon, and chocolate beignet. Along with the shrimp and grits and the fried chicken (there's a specific name for it but I forgot). The crawfish and chocolate beignet was so so so good! You MUST ORDER IT WHEN YOU GO!! As for the Shrimp and Grits it was so cheesy and gooey and just amazing... I am drooling as I am typing this and thinking about it right now. They also give you a good amount of shrimp! I tried the fried chicken it was so good also, the greens were delicious! My favorite part of that dish would have to be the biscuit! It was so soft and yet fell apart so nicely and just melted in your mouth. It was just great! Also, order the watermelon sweet tea it's the perfect drink to go with your meal!

This was our first time here. The wait was a little long. Yet, the food was worth the wait. The omelette was excellent. My wife had the pecan pancakes. Great visit. Great service. We will be back.

The Beignets are the best here and the shrimp and bacon grits!! My friend and I came for brunch in a Saturday. The wait was about 30 mins which wasn't too bad. I had read reviews where people had to wait over 2 hours so I was happy about that. They had a cute cafe down the way that we were able to wait in until our name was called. We ordered the beignet flight, catfish benedict, shrimp and grits, and a crab beignet which was a special that day. EVERYTHING was AMAZING. My taste buds were so happy!! I do plan to come back here soon!!

I know good soul food and this is just not it, the crawfish beignets are not flavorful at all were very bready. I also got the oyster poboy which didn't taste good and I couldn't finish it. Mac N Cheese was good and so was the fried chicken but those are both hard to mess up so three stars overall. The lady at the front is also really sweet and patient!

After returning to Brenda's again for brunch, I'm extra appreciative of how it's different from all the New American brunch places that are a dime-a-dozen in the city. We ordered shrimp and grits, which were wonderfully cheesy, creamy, and with a nice kick. This was the dish that had everyone at the table raving, but I thought that the fried chicken was a close second-place contender. The fried chicken comes with one large breast piece and a thigh, a towering flaky biscuit, and french fries. The chucks. was probably among the best fried chicken I've ever had; it wasn't overly greasy, and even the breast meat was juicy and flavorful. The fries were disappointing -- limp and reminiscent of the kind that I used to get from my high school cafeteria. In my opinion, when something is deep-fried and lacks crispy texture, it just seems like a waste of fat, oil, and calories. We also ordered an andouille sausage and cheddar omelette, which was equally satisfying. I didn't care for the potato hash that came as a side, since I prefer my breakfast potatoes to be on the crispy side. Next time, I would order the grits instead. Brenda's is very, very good at what it does, but I found it a little bit on the heavy side for brunch; maybe I'm just not used to eating so much heavy, fried food first thing in the morning! Still, everything we ordered was delicious, and it's a good change of pace from the typical brunch places that are so plentiful in San Francisco.

The food was absolutely delicious. My friend and I got the BFC chicken dinner(subbed Mac due to pork in greens) and the spicy pasta orleans. The chicken in the BFC was tender and had a great flavor to it, the biscuit was flaky and fluffy with great jams accompanying it and the Mac and cheese was out of this world. The spicy pasta orleans might have been the pasta dish I've had. It had a great assortment of seafood and was rich, and the flavor was amazing. Hope to try other items on the menu when back in the area.

Brenda's is one of the most hyped brunches in SF, so I had to try it out! But given my hesitation of waiting indefinitely for food, I came with my friend right as they opened, and we were seated right away! The person seating the crowd wasn't the most friendly (I can imagine why), but our server was extremely nice. To start, we ordered the flight of stuffed beignets, which came with one plain (meh), one apple (not bad!), one chocolate (too full to try by the end!), and one crawfish. Get the crawfish!! The filling was creamy, decadent, and delicious, and instead of powdered sugar, it was sprinkled with paprika for a subtle but spicy kick! We then split two different entrees. I went for the shrimp and grits, which were absolutely covered with cream, butter, and melted cheddar cheese--very, very heavy stuff! In fact, I would probably say that this dish was unnecessarily heavy--it had so much fat that the grease no longer added to the deliciousness of the dish. The second entrée we had was the Andouille sausage & cheddar omelette, which we had with a tomato-y potato hash and a huge cream biscuit. I felt that the omelette was a little too greasy from the sausage (again, a little unnecessarily so), but the sides were pretty decent! Do be warned--this was a LOT of food (pretty huge portions) and we ended up taking quite a bit to go. Even so, the entire meal felt very heavy (kind of to be expected for Southern cooking). Was it good? Yes. But perhaps not wait-two-hours-in-line good.

SOUL food is right! I've raved about Brenda's many times before, but had to update my review to give major props to this place for hosting live jazz music on Sundays. While this place is usually jam packed and hectic, the vibe completely shifts with Goucho Gypsy Jazz in the mix, creating the perfect atmosphere for munching on beignets and bobbing your head to the groove. Brenda's dream of sharing her hometown with San Francisco has been a definite success, as this place embodies all of New Orleans' funkiness, rich cuisine, and lively music. As a long time lover of jazz, (and delicious food) I'm so happy this place is here and doing well. I know Brenda just expanded to 2 additional locations- you bet I'll be bookmarking those and Yelping those in the very, very near future! Hope everyone reading this gets the chance to come out here for an authentic taste of NAWLINS!!

    After returning to Brenda's again for brunch, I'm extra appreciative of how it's different from all the New American brunch places that are a dime-a-dozen in the city.

    We ordered shrimp and grits, which were wonderfully cheesy, creamy, and with a nice kick. This was the dish that had everyone at the table raving, but I thought that the fried chicken was a close second-place contender.

    The fried chicken comes with one large breast piece and a thigh, a towering flaky biscuit, and french fries. The chucks. was probably among the best fried chicken I've ever had; it wasn't overly greasy, and even the breast meat was juicy and flavorful. The fries were disappointing -- limp and reminiscent of the kind that I used to get from my high school cafeteria. In my opinion, when something is deep-fried and lacks crispy texture, it just seems like a waste of fat, oil, and calories.

    We also ordered an andouille sausage and cheddar omelette, which was equally satisfying. I didn't care for the potato hash that came as a side, since I prefer my breakfast potatoes to be on the crispy side. Next time, I would order the grits instead.

    Brenda's is very, very good at what it does, but I found it a little bit on the heavy side for brunch; maybe I'm just not used to eating so much heavy, fried food first thing in the morning! Still, everything we ordered was delicious, and it's a good change of pace from the typical brunch places that are so plentiful in San Francisco.

    3/30/2014Previous review

    We came here around 5pm on a Saturday night since it's not exactly in the best part of town, and there were still a few tables open. Good thing we were early because the place only seats about 30 people and the line got long, fast.

    Crawfish beignets (5/5) - This reminded me of a Hawaiian roll, wonderfully flavored with Cajun seasoning, and bursting with crawfish. We each finished one, but I could have easily eaten more. This was one of my favorite parts of the meal.

    Shrimp and grits (4/4) - this was good, but a little too cheesy for me.

    Fried chicken (5/5) - I had a couple bites of my friend's fried chicken and had instant food envy/regret over my own order. If I come back, I'd get this.

    You can tell this is the kind of place where pretty much everything on the menu is solid.  This place was actually originally recommended by a friend for brunch, and I'd love to come back and try this breakfast spread.

The second entrée we had was the Andouille sausage & cheddar omelette, which we had with a tomato-y potato hash and a huge cream biscuit. I felt that the omelette was a little too greasy from the sausage (again, a little unnecessarily so), but the sides were pretty decent!

    Do be warned--this was a LOT of food (pretty huge portions) and we ended up taking quite a bit to go. Even so, the entire meal felt very heavy (kind of to be expected for Southern cooking). Was it good? Yes. But perhaps not wait-two-hours-in-line good.

    2/18/2013Previous review

    Both the breakfast and lunch here are crazy delicious! I have tried the goat cheese & shrimp omelette, crawfish beignets, clam fry with grits and their shrimp po'boy which all seem to fit the theme of soul food that is super heavy and fried, but sooo friggen tasty.

    The plain beignets (French-inspired fried doughnuts) are worth ordering a bunch and bringing to friends. When I did this I only received positive reviews from the smiling faces of what looked to be a bunch of hungry CRACK addicts. (They pile on plenty of powdered sugar on those babies.)

    TIP #1: If you're eating in, don't forget that the watermelon iced tea is bottomless! Perfect for if you order the somewhat spicy crawfish beignets on a hot day.

    TIP #2: You can save so much time during the crowded lunch rush by ordering the food to-go here. Walk things down to Civic Center Plaza and eat outside if the TL's sidewalks don't suit your tastes. This place gets packed right from when they open, so plan accordingly.

By the time we left the restaurant was crowded but thankfully I was able to be wheeled out through the other entrance.
